INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (55,1,'2013-02-01 00:44:48','2013-02-01 05:44:48','Which city has the highest demand for wheelchair taxi in Canada? Which countries do people search for wheelchair transportation on the internet?\r\n\r\nAt least <a href=\"http://www.google.ca/trends/\">Google Trends</a> sheds some lights on trying to answer some of these questions. Google exposes where and when the search happened the most given the search keyword. I tried \'wheelchair\'.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend1.jpg\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid black;\" alt=\"search traffic for wheelchair\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend1.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"428\" /></a> search traffic for \'wheelchair\'[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe page shows \'wheelchair\' worldwide search traffic since 2004 to present. We can see that the traffic came mostly from United States, but a lot of traffic also came from Canada as well. I wanted to see which city people searched for \'wheelchair\', so I clicked \"City\" link to see the data.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"398\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend2.jpg\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid black;\" alt=\"the list of cities from where people searched for wheelchair\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend2.jpg\" width=\"398\" height=\"387\" /></a> The list of cities from where people searched for \'wheelchair\'[/caption]\r\n\r\nNote that the number besides the blue bar represent the search volume relative to the highest point on the chart, which is always 100. So in this case the search traffic for \'wheelchair\' from Toronto is about two third of the traffic coming from Dublin. And Toronto is the only city listed here.\r\n\r\nWe can see from the page that wheelchair search traffic is steady, and also a lot of people who searched for \'wheelchair\' usually also searched for keywords like \'wheelchair accessible\', \'wheelchair rental\', \'electric wheelchair\', etc. Since we are a wheelchair accessible transportation company, I typed \'wheelchair taxi\' to see what is the search trend for this keyword.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend3.jpg\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid black;\" alt=\"search trend for wheelchair taxi\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend3.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"377\" /></a> search trend for \'wheelchair taxi\'[/caption]\r\n\r\nSurprisingly there isn\'t much traffic for this throughout Canada, but the most of traffic comes from British Columbia and Ontario only. The city-level information is not available for this keyword. I think the reason is that the search volume for this keyword is substantially smaller than \'wheelchair\' or other popular keywords, so the information is too granular to expose to public.\r\n\r\nThe keyword for \'wheelchair transportation\' shows the similar graph.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend4.jpg\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid black;\" alt=\"wheelchair transportation\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/trend4.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"370\" /></a> keyword \'wheelchair transportation\'[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe pattern looks similar to \'wheelchair taxi\' except that the traffic is now highly concentrated on Ontario. Still overall the search volume is very small.\r\n\r\nI think there are not much data to draw any conclusion in this case because there aren\'t much traffic for wheelchair transportation in general. But I think Google Trends is a handy tool to help assess what people search for the most and quickly see where and when people look for stuff.','Wheelchair on Google Trends','','inherit','closed','open','','35-revision-10','','','2013-02-01 00:44:48','2013-02-01 05:44:48','',35,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/35-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(75,1,'2013-02-01 23:58:03','2013-02-02 04:58:03','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\r\n\r\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\r\n\r\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\r\n<h2>Slope</h2>\r\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\r\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\r\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\r\n\r\nMaintenance\r\n\r\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSlope, landing experience, visibility, and maintenance are some of the things to consider when installing the accessible ramps. It is a bit surprising that Ontario (or Canada) does not provide any regulation on how the ramps should be installed. Since no regulation is enforced there are many ramps out there that are just inadequate to use. The wheelchair ramps at least should meet the points mentioned above to provide better accessibility to wheelchair users.','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-18','','','2013-02-01 23:58:03','2013-02-02 04:58:03','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-18/',0,'revision','',0),(16,1,'2013-01-25 07:02:15','2013-01-25 07:02:15','    <header class=\'header-background\'>\r\n      <img src=\'wp-content/uploads/2013/01/wheelchair.jpg\' alt=\'wheelchair transportation\'>\r\n      <div class=\'container\'>\r\n        <div class=\'header-caption\'>\r\n          <h1>\r\n            Non-Emergency Wheelchair Accessible Transportation Services in <abbr title=\'Greater Toronto Area\'>GTA</abbr>.\r\n          </h1>\r\n          <p class=\'lead hidden-phone\'>\r\n            We are dedicated drivers trained to provide wheelchair-accessible transportation services to people with special needs and disabilities. We operate in Greater Toronto Area and beyond. <a href=\'/about/\'><button class=\'btn btn-primary\' type=\'button\'>View More</button></a>\r\n            <div class=\"fb-like\" data-href=\"http://www.facebook.com/SaveWheelchairTrans\" data-send=\"false\" data-layout=\"button_count\" data-width=\"450\" data-show-faces=\"true\"></div>\r\n            <div style=\'padding-top:1px\' class=\"g-plusone\" data-size=\"small\" data-href