d stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\n\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\n\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\n<h2>Slope</h2>\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"569\"]<img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"569\" height=\"569\" /> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-8','','','2013-02-01 23:43:21','2013-02-02 04:43:21','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(65,1,'2013-02-01 23:44:21','2013-02-02 04:44:21','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\n\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\n\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\n<h2>Slope</h2>\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-9','','','2013-02-01 23:44:21','2013-02-02 04:44:21','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(66,1,'2013-02-01 23:47:36','2013-02-02 04:47:36','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\n\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\n\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\n<h2>Slope</h2>\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\n\nMaintenance\n\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\n\n&nbsp;','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-10','','','2013-02-01 23:47:36','2013-02-02 04:47:36','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(67,1,'2013-02-01 23:47:57','2013-02-02 04:47:57','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\r\n\r\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\r\n\r\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\r\n<h2>Slope</h2>\r\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\r\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\r\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\r\n\r\nMaintenance\r\n\r\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-11','','','2013-02-01 23:47:57','2013-02-02 04:47:57','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-11/',0,'revision','',0),(68,1,'2013-02-01 23:47:59','2013-02-02 04:47:59','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\r\n\r\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\r\n\r\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\r\n<h2>Slope</h2>\r\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\r\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\r\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\r\n\r\nMaintenance\r\n\r\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-12','','','2013-02-01 23:47:59','2013-02-02 04:47:59','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(69,1,'2013-02-01 23:49:55','2013-02-02 04:49:55','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\r\n\r\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\r\n\r\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\r\n<h2>Slope</h2>\r\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\r\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\r\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\r\n\r\nMaintenance\r\n\r\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSlope, landing experience, visibility, and maintenance are some of the things to consider when installing the accessible ramps. It is a bit surprising that Ontario (or Canada) does not provide any regulation on how the ramps should be installed. Since no regulation is enforced there are many ramps out there that are just inadequate to use. The wheelchair ramps at least should meet the points mentioned above to provide better accessibility to wheelchair users.','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-13','','','2013-02-01 23:49:55','2013-02-02 04:49:55','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(70,1,'2013-02-01 23:49:57','2013-02-02 04:49:57','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\r\n\r\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\r\n\r\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\r\n<h2>Slope</h2>\r\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\r\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\r\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\r\n\r\nMaintenance\r\n\r\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<img alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSlope, landing experience, visibility, and maintenance are some of the things to consider when installing the accessible ramps. It is a bit surprising that Ontario (or Canada) does not provide any regulation on how the ramps should be installed. Since no regulation is enforced there are many ramps out there that are just inadequate to use. The wheelchair ramps at least should meet the points mentioned above to provide better accessibility to wheelchair users.','What makes a good wheelchair ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-14','','','2013-02-01 23:49:57','2013-02-02 04:49:57','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(7