amps. It is a bit surprising that Ontario (or Canada) does not provide any regulation on how the ramps should be installed. Since no regulation is enforced there are many ramps out there that are just inadequate to use. The wheelchair ramps at least should meet the points mentioned above to provide better accessibility to wheelchair users.','What Makes a Good Wheelchair Ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-21','','','2013-02-02 14:23:38','2013-02-02 19:23:38','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-21/',0,'revision','',0),(79,1,'2013-02-02 14:23:40','2013-02-02 19:23:40','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\r\n\r\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\r\n\r\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\r\n<h2>Slope</h2>\r\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"