een mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSlope, landing experience, visibility, and maintenance are some of the things to consider when installing the accessible ramps. It is a bit surprising that Ontario (or Canada) does not provide any regulation on how the ramps should be installed. Since no regulation is enforced there are many ramps out there that are just inadequate to use. The wheelchair ramps at least should meet the points mentioned above to provide better accessibility to wheelchair users.','What Makes a Good Wheelchair Ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-24','','','2013-02-02 14:25:12','2013-02-02 19:25:12','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-24/',0,'revision','',0),(83,1,'2013-02-05 00:17:27','2013-02-05 05:17:27','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\n\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\n\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\n<h2>Slope</h2>\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada<sup>[1]</sup>, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\n<h2>Maintenance</h2>\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]\n\nSlope, landing experience, visibility, and maintenance are some of the things to consider when installing the accessible ramps. It is a bit surprising that Ontario (or Canada) does not provide any regulation on how the ramps should be installed. Since no regulation is enforced there are many ramps out there that are just inadequate to use. The wheelchair ramps at least should meet the points mentioned above to provide better accessibility to wheelchair users.\n\n[1] In fact, Ontario does specify 1:12 ratio for the ramps in the billing code: <a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_060350_e.htm\">Ontario building code</a>.','What Makes a Good Wheelchair Ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-autosave','','','2013-02-05 00:17:27','2013-02-05 05:17:27','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(84,1,'2013-02-02 14:29:07','2013-02-02 19:29:07','Wheelchair-accessible ramps are essential for easier access to buildings and stores that have doorsteps and stairs to their entrances. Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA) mandates that all the businesses regardless of their sizes ensure their services are accessible to people with disabilities. And having wheelchair-accessible ramps could remove physical barriers to enter their businesses, which is the first step to comply with AODA.\r\n\r\nAODA, however, does not regulate the wheelchair ramp designs, so we often see many poorly designed ramps that not only cause negative experiences but also pose a barrier that can be dangerous to people.\r\n\r\nSo, what can be a good wheelchair accessible ramp? How should we install the ramps so that they really benefit people in wheelchairs? There are few things to consider, which are 1) slope, 2) landing experiences, 3) visibility, and 4) maintenance.\r\n<h2>Slope</h2>\r\nThe ramp slope should be low enough to make the climb easier for wheelchair users. If the angle is too steep then it will make the ramp difficult to climb and also could be dangerous. There is currently no regulation regarding the wheelchair ramp slope in Canada, but other countries including United States and United Kingdom require a 1:12 slope for wheelchair ramps. This means 1\'\' of rise requires 12\'\' of ramp.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"wheelchair ramp with lower slope\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-1TvlQzANhAw/UQyWYggQYmI/AAAAAAAAAMI/_5RHTBn2NwA/s569/dec8fa726cea11e2990322000a9f192c_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> It is common that slopes \"go around\" the stairs to have a lower slope and longer length.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Landing Experience</h2>\r\nLanding experience is as much important as climb up the ramp. Usually the landing side of the ramp should have enough space to rest and proceed towards the building entrance. We often notice that many businesses do not provide good landing experiences even if they provide wheelchair ramps on their doorsteps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"wheelchair ramp with negative landing experience\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-etTSTMsbFHg/UQyWX9-YdAI/AAAAAAAAAL4/clO_HlD0YPI/s569/521565_411351278952390_1771367635_n.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> Wheelchair users will have hard time pulling open these doors while on the ramp.[/caption]\r\n<h2>Visibility</h2>\r\nThe wheelchair ramps should be installed close to the stairs and must be visible and apparent to people who need them. Ideally the wheelchair users should be able to find the ramps without any sign, but if the ramps are somehow hard to find due to constructions or temporary disruptions, there must be a sign indicating an alternate route to wheelchair ramps.\r\n\r\n<h2>Maintenance</h2>\r\n\r\nWinter involves heavy snowfall in Greater Toronto Area and Ontario in general. Maintenance is necessary to ensure that there is no snow accumulation that could block both the approach and the landing of the ramp. This problem could be seen mostly in the sidewalk ramps, where snow is often plowed onto the sidewalk to build the banks and block the ramps.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"snow covering sidewalk ramps\" src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-ENvKGPAHpbU/UQyWYUNrfoI/AAAAAAAAAMA/iYKC7mWA4m4/s569/c0797b9a6cf011e2a94622000a1fbd9f_7.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"500\" /></a> After heavy snowfall, the hard-packed snow could block the sidewalk ramps.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSlope, landing experience, visibility, and maintenance are some of the things to consider when installing the accessible ramps. It is a bit surprising that Ontario (or Canada) does not provide any regulation on how the ramps should be installed. Since no regulation is enforced there are many ramps out there that are just inadequate to use. The wheelchair ramps at least should meet the points mentioned above to provide better accessibility to wheelchair users.','What Makes a Good Wheelchair Ramp?','','inherit','closed','open','','56-revision-25','','','2013-02-02 14:29:07','2013-02-02 19:29:07','',56,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/56-revision-25/',0,'revision','',0),(85,1,'2013-02-11 01:00:32','2013-02-11 06:00:32','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88 \" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The AODA[/caption]\r\n\r\nThere is a news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with the Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or there is a more specific example of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? How does the AODA enforce the accessibility? In this post we will talk about the purpose of the AODA, how the AODA complements the ODA, and what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>The difference between the ODA and the AODA.</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Bill only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Bill requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA Compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n\r\nOther four standards are in progress to set the schedules of compliance. For Employment standard, the current schedule is that the Government of Ontario must be compliant by January 1, 2013, large public sector organizations by January 1, 2014, small public sector organizations by January 1, 2015, large organizations by January 1, 2016, and small organizations by January 1, 2017.\r\n<h2>The Implication to the Wheelchair Users in Ontario</h2>\r\nThe Accessibility Standards for Customer Service is the standard, which applies to any organization that provides goods and services to customers. It sets out the obligations that the organizations must now provide their goods and services in a way that is accessible to people with disabilities. For example, all the restaurants in Ontario should already have established their businesses accessible to customers in wheelchairs.\r\n\r\nToronto Transit Commision (TTC) has made their <a href=\"http://www.ttc.ca/TTC_Accessibility/Accessibility_for_Ontarians_with_Disabilities_AODA/Accessible_Customer_Service_Policy_Statement/index.jsp\">Accessible Customer Service Policy public</a>.\r\n\r\nTransportation Standards will be rolled out to public transportation providers between 2011 and 2017, and every transportation service provider should ensure that all of the transportation vehicles be equipped with lifting devices or ramps by January 1, 2013. Also they should not charge people with disabilities higher fare.\r\n\r\nBuilt Environment Standards focus on removing barriers in public spaces and buildings. For the public spaces, however, the standard only applies to new construction and major changes to existing features. This excludes the already built hiking trails and parks that are not wheelchair-accessible.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','publish','closed','open','','accessibility-for-ontarians-with-disabilities-act-aoda','','','2013-02-13 10:27:26','2013-02-13 15:27:26','',0,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/?p=85',0,'post','',0),(86,1,'2013-02-08 22:50:06','2013-02-09 03:50:06','You might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is,\n\nResources\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.</span></li>\n	<li>Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act.</li>\n	<li></li>\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision','','','2013-02-08 22:50:06','2013-02-09 03:50:06','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(87,1,'2013-02-08 22:51:06','2013-02-09 03:51:06','You might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is,\n\nResources\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\n	<li></li>\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-2','','','2013-02-08 22:51:06','2013-02-09 03:51:06','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(88,1,'2013-02-08 22:54:30','2013-02-09 03:54:30','','aoda','The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.','inherit','closed','open','','aoda','','','2013-02-08 22:54:30','2013-02-09 03:54:30','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(89,1,'2013-02-08 22:54:43','2013-02-09 03:54:43','You might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\n\nResources\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\n	<li></li>\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-3','','','2013-02-08 22:54:43','2013-02-09 03:54:43',''