www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\n	<li></li>\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-5','','','2013-02-08 22:55:43','2013-02-09 03:55:43','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(92,1,'2013-02-08 22:59:48','2013-02-09 03:59:48','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-6','','','2013-02-08 22:59:48','2013-02-09 03:59:48','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(93,1,'2013-02-08 22:59:50','2013-02-09 03:59:50','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-7','','','2013-02-08 22:59:50','2013-02-09 03:59:50','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(96,1,'2013-02-08 23:04:37','2013-02-09 04:04:37','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA consists of five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-10','','','2013-02-08 23:04:37','2013-02-09 04:04:37','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(94,1,'2013-02-08 23:04:00','2013-02-09 04:04:00','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>How does the Bill enforce the accessibility standards to the organizations in Ontario?</h2>\r\nThe AODA consists of five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-8','','','2013-02-08 23:04:00','2013-02-09 04:04:00','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(95,1,'2013-02-08 23:04:03','2013-02-09 04:04:03','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>How does the Bill enforce the accessibility standards to the organizations in Ontario?</h2>\r\nThe AODA consists of five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-9','','','2013-02-08 23:04:03','2013-02-09 04:04:03','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(97,1,'2013-02-08 23:04:39','2013-02-09 04:04:39','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA consists of five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-11','','','2013-02-08 23:04:39','2013-02-09 04:04:39','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-11/',0,'revision','',0),(98,1,'2013-02-08 23:10:12','2013-02-09 04:10:12','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-12','','','2013-02-08 23:10:12','2013-02-09 04:10:12','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(99,1,'2013-02-08 23:10:14','2013-02-09 04:10:14','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-13','','','2013-02-08 23:10:14','2013-02-09 04:10:14','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(112,1,'2013-02-10 12:16:20','2013-02-10 17:16:20','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88 \" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The AODA[/caption]\r\n\r\nThere was a news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or there is a more specific example of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>The difference between the ODA and the AODA.</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n\r\nOther four standards are in progress to set the schedules of compliance. For Employment standard, the current schedule is that the Government of Ontario must be compliant by January 1, 2013, large public sector organizations by January 1, 2014, small public sector organizations by January 1, 2015, large organizations by January 1, 2016, and small organizations by January 1, 2017.\r\n<h2>The implication to the wheelchair users in Ontario</h2>\r\nThe Accessibility Standards for Customer Service is the standard, which applies to any organization that provides goods and services to customers. It sets out the obligations that the organizations must now provide their goods and services in a way that is accessible to people with disabilities. For example, all the restaurants in Ontario should already have established their businesses accessible to customers in wheelchairs.\r\n\r\nToronto Transit Commision (TTC) has made their <a href=\"http://www.ttc.ca/TTC_Accessibility/Accessibility_for_Ontarians_with_Disabilities_AODA/Accessible_Customer_Service_Policy_Statement/index.jsp\">Accessible Customer Service Policy public</a>.\r\n\r\nTransportation Standards will be rolled out to public transportation providers between 2011 and 2017, and every transportation service provider should ensure that all of the transportation vehicles be equipped with lifting devices or ramps by January 1, 2013. Also they should not charge people with disabilities higher fare.\r\n\r\nBuilt Environment Standards focus on removing barriers in public spaces and buildings. For the public spaces, however, the standard only applies to new construction and major changes to existing features. This excludes the already built hiking trails and parks that are not wheelchair-accessible.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-25','','','2013-02-10 12:16:20','2013-02-10 17:16:20','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-25/',0,'revision','',0),(104,1,'2013-02-08 23:19:53','2013-02-09 04:19:53','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88 \" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The AODA[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>The difference between the ODA and the AODA.</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n\r\nOther four standards are in progress to set the schedules of compliance. For Employment standard, the current schedule is that the Government of Ontario must be compliant by January 1, 2013, large public sector organizations by January 1, 2014, small public sector organizations by January 1, 2015, large organizations by January 1, 2016, and small organizations by January 1, 2017.\r\n<h2>The implication to the wheelchair users in Ontario</h2>\r\nThe Accessibility Standards for Customer Service is the standard, which applies to any organization that provides goods and services to customers. It sets out the obligations that the organizations must now provide their goods and services in a way that is accessible to people with disabilities. For example, all the restaurants in Ontario should already have established their businesses accessible to customers in wheelchairs.\r\n\r\nToronto Transit Commision (TTC) has made their <a href=\"http://www.ttc.ca/TTC_Accessibility/Accessibility_for_Ontarians_with_Disabilities_AODA/Accessible_Customer_Service_Policy_Statement/index.jsp\">Accessible Customer Service Policy public</a>.\r\n\r\nTransportation Standards will be rolled out to public transportation providers between 2011 and 2017, and every transportation service provider should ensure that all of the transportation vehicles be equipped with lifting devices or ramps by January 1, 2013. Also they should not charge people with disabilities higher fare.\r\n\r\nBuilt Environment Standards focus on removing barriers in public spaces and buildings. For the public spaces, however, the standard only applies to new construction and major changes to existing features. This excludes the already built hiking trails and parks that are not wheelchair-accessible.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-18','','','2013-02-08 23:19:53','2013-02-09 04:19:53','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-18/',0,'revision','',0),(100,1,'2013-02-08 23:18:10','2013-02-09 04:18:10','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n\r\nOther four standards are in progress to set the schedules of compliance. For Employment standard, the current schedule is that the Government of Ontario must be compliant by January 1, 2013, large public sector organizations by January 1, 2014, small public sector organizations by January 1, 2015, large organizations by January 1, 2016, and small organizations by January 1, 2017.\r\n<h2>The implication to the wheelchair users in Ontario</h2>\r\nThe Accessibility Standards for Customer Service is the standard, which applies to any organization that provides goods and services to customers. It sets out the obligations that the organizations must now provide their goods and services in a way that is accessible to people with disabilities. For example, all the restaurants in Ontario should already have established their businesses accessible to customers in wheelchairs.\r\n\r\nToronto Transit Commision (TTC) has made their <a href=\"http://www.ttc.ca/TTC_Accessibility/Accessibility_for_Ontarians_with_Disabilities_AODA/Accessible_Customer_Service_Policy_Statement/index.jsp\">Accessible Customer Service Policy public</a>.\r\n\r\nTransportation Standards will be rolled out to public transportation providers between 2011 and 2017, and every transportation service provider should ensure that all of the transportation vehicles be equipped with lifting devices or ramps by January 1, 2013. Also they should not charge people with disabilities higher fare.\r\n\r\nBuilt Environment Standards focus on removing barriers in public spaces and buildings. For the public spaces, however, the standard only applies to new construction and major changes to existing features. This excludes the already built hiking trails and parks that are not wheelchair-accessible.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-14','','','2013-02-08 23:18:10','2013-02-09 04:18:10','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(101,1,'2013-02-08 23:18:13','2013-02-09 04:18:13','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88\" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.[/caption]\r\n\r\nYou might have heard about the news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or you might even have heard about more specific examples of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? Let\'s take a look at what the AODA really is, how the AODA complements the ODA, what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>What is the difference between the ODA and the AODA?</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Act only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Act requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the accessibility plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n\r\nOther four standards are in progress to set the schedules of compliance. For Employment standard, the current schedule is that the Government of Ontario must be compliant by January 1, 2013, large public sector organizations by January 1, 2014, small public sector organizations by January 1, 2015, large organizations by January 1, 2016, and small organizations by January 1, 2017.\r\n<h2>The implication to the wheelchair users in Ontario</h2>\r\nThe Accessibility Standards for Customer Service is the standard, which applies to any orga