ther level.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-21','','','2013-02-13 01:47:46','2013-02-13 06:47:46','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-21/',0,'revision','',0),(152,1,'2013-02-13 01:47:49','2013-02-13 06:47:49','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: an entrance next to Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a life in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this life is that you cannot get the lift to your level if it is on the other level.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-22','','','2013-02-13 01:47:49','2013-02-13 06:47:49','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-22/',0,'revision','',0),(153,1,'2013-02-13 01:49:35','2013-02-13 06:49:35','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: an entrance next to Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other level.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-23','','','2013-02-13 01:49:35','2013-02-13 06:49:35','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-23/',0,'revision','',0),(154,1,'2013-02-13 01:49:37','2013-02-13 06:49:37','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: an entrance next to Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other level.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-24','','','2013-02-13 01:49:37','2013-02-13 06:49:37','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-24/',0,'revision','',0),(156,1,'2013-02-13 01:50:10','2013-02-13 06:50:10','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: an entrance next to Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-26','','','2013-02-13 01:50:10','2013-02-13 06:50:10','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-26/',0,'revision','',0),(157,1,'2013-02-11 07:23:34','2013-02-11 12:23:34','[caption id=\"attachment_88\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda.gif\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-88 \" alt=\"The Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act.\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/aoda-300x300.gif\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> The AODA[/caption]\r\n\r\nThere is a news regarding <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/business/small_business/people/2012/12/26/taking_proactive_steps_to_comply_with_the_aoda_is_a_smart_business_move.html\">the businesses trying to comply with the Accessibility for the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)</a>, or there is a more specific example of <a href=\"http://www.starbucks.ca/responsibility/diversity/aoda\">Starbucks announcing the commitment to comply with the AODA</a>. The AODA is, as its name implies, an Act to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities in Ontario. But how does it improve the accessibility? We already have the similar Bill: the Ontarians with Disabilities Act (ODA), which was enacted before the AODA. So what is the difference between the AODA and the ODA? How does the AODA enforce the accessibility? In this post we will talk about the purpose of the AODA, how the AODA complements the ODA, and what is its implication for wheelchair users in Ontario.\r\n<h2>What is the AODA and when was it enacted?</h2>\r\nThe AODA is the Act to mandate the accessibility standards and regulations to every business in Ontario to improve the accessibility for people with disabilities using their services. The AODA has been enacted in 2005, and became the law as of January 1, 2012.\r\n<h2>The difference between the ODA and the AODA.</h2>\r\nThe ODA has been enacted in 2002 to \"improve opportunities for persons with disabilities and to provide for their involvement in the identification, removal, and prevention of barriers to their full participation in the life of the province\". The Bill mandates the government\'s commitment to remove the barriers that people with disabilities experience to participating in the society events.\r\n\r\nThe problems with this Bill, however, are that first of all, the Bill did not specify the time-frame for the government to create the barrier-free environment. Secondly, this Bill only applies to the public sectors and left the private sectors unaffected by the Bill. And lastly, the Bill requires the government sectors to prepare accessibility plans as part of their annual planning process, but does not enforce them to implement the plans.\r\n\r\nSo here comes the AODA; the AODA has been enacted in 2005 to complement the ODA with deadlines, enforcement, and penalties. The purpose of the AODA is to develop, implement, and enforce accessibility standards to every organization in Ontario with respect to goods, services, facilities, employment, buildings, structures, and premises, by January 1, 2025.\r\n<h2>The Bill Enforcement</h2>\r\nThe AODA enforces five standards: Customer Service, Transportation, Information &amp; Communications, Employment, and Built Environment. The AODA requires organizations to create accessibility plans indicating how the organizations will implement to meet the regulation for each accessibility standard by the designated deadline. The Act details the procedure the individual organization should take to propose the initial plan, determine the time-frame, and finalize the process. The Act also specifies the government inspection rules and the penalties of the organizations that fail to meet the standard by the deadline.\r\n\r\nEach standard has different deadline. For example, the deadline for the Customer Service standard was January 1, 2012. This means that all the organizations in Ontario must now be compliant with the Customer Service standards since 2012.\r\n<h2>The Current Status of the AODA compliance</h2>\r\nAs mentioned above, the accessibility standards for Customer Service has been rolled out and its compliance is mandatory for all the organizations in Ontario, whether they be government, business, or charity organizations.\r\n\r\nOther four standards are in progress to set the schedules of compliance. For Employment standard, the current schedule is that the Government of Ontario must be compliant by January 1, 2013, large public sector organizations by January 1, 2014, small public sector organizations by January 1, 2015, large organizations by January 1, 2016, and small organizations by January 1, 2017.\r\n<h2>The implication to the wheelchair users in Ontario</h2>\r\nThe Accessibility Standards for Customer Service is the standard, which applies to any organization that provides goods and services to customers. It sets out the obligations that the organizations must now provide their goods and services in a way that is accessible to people with disabilities. For example, all the restaurants in Ontario should already have established their businesses accessible to customers in wheelchairs.\r\n\r\nToronto Transit Commision (TTC) has made their <a href=\"http://www.ttc.ca/TTC_Accessibility/Accessibility_for_Ontarians_with_Disabilities_AODA/Accessible_Customer_Service_Policy_Statement/index.jsp\">Accessible Customer Service Policy public</a>.\r\n\r\nTransportation Standards will be rolled out to public transportation providers between 2011 and 2017, and every transportation service provider should ensure that all of the transportation vehicles be equipped with lifting devices or ramps by January 1, 2013. Also they should not charge people with disabilities higher fare.\r\n\r\nBuilt Environment Standards focus on removing barriers in public spaces and buildings. For the public spaces, however, the standard only applies to new construction and major changes to existing features. This excludes the already built hiking trails and parks that are not wheelchair-accessible.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\"><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05a11_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</span></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_01o32_e.htm\">Text of the Ontarians with Disabilities Act</a>.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/regs/english/elaws_regs_070429_e.htm\">Text of the Accessibility Standards for Customer Service</a>.</li>\r\n</ul>','Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA)','','inherit','closed','open','','85-revision-40','','','2013-02-11 07:23:34','2013-02-11 12:23:34','',85,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/85-revision-40/',0,'revision','',0),(158,1,'2013-02-13 02:39:40','2013-02-13 07:39:40','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: an entrance next to Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-27','','','2013-02-13 02:39:40','2013-02-13 07:39:40','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-27/',0,'revision','',0),(159,1,'2013-02-13 10:28:28','2013-02-13 15:28:28','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: an entrance next to Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-28','','','2013-02-13 10:28:28','2013-02-13 15:28:28','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-28/',0,'revision','',0),(160,1,'2013-02-13 21:37:08','2013-02-14 02:37:08','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: an entrance next to Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-29','','','2013-02-13 21:37:08','2013-02-14 02:37:08','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-29/',0,'revision','',0),(161,1,'2013-02-13 21:37:53','2013-02-14 02:37:53','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-30','','','2013-02-13 21:37:53','2013-02-14 02:37:53','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-30/',0,'revision','',0),(162,1,'2013-02-13 21:37:56','2013-02-14 02:37:56','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-31','','','2013-02-13 21:37:56','2013-02-14 02:37:56','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-31/',0,'revision','',0),(163,1,'2013-02-13 22:38:52','2013-02-14 03:38:52','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\n\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\n\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\n\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\n\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\n\nThe following video clips show how to get to the subway platform from those entrances.\n\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\n\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\n\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\n\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\n\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\n\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\n\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\n\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\n\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\n\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\n\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\n\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\n<ol>\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-autosave','','','2013-02-13 22:38:52','2013-02-14 03:38:52','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(164,1,'2013-02-13 21:41:30','2013-02-14 02:41:30','[caption id=\"attachment_145\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-145\" alt=\"Finch TTC Station\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/finch-300x171.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"171\" /></a> Finch TTC Station[/caption]\r\n\r\nFinch TTC Station is the most northernmost station in Yonge-subway line and is wheelchair-accessible. I am not a wheelchair user, but I wanted to see what are the wheelchair accessible routes to the subway platform from outside if I were on a wheelchair.\r\n\r\nThere are about 6 pedestrian entrances to the station, and half of them have accessible elevators installed: Kiss-N-Ride, Go Finch Bus Terminal, and North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"375\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-WO73qaZqAHo/URnQPBzsHBI/AAAAAAAAAN4/YtYFf2u9kck/s1054/IMG_20130209_162753.jpg\" width=\"375\" height=\"500\" /></a> An elevator next to Kiss-N-Ride.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\"><img alt=\"An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-SkHVaW2deDU/URnQOODoYwI/AAAAAAAAANs/E_1SihzR5CA/s1257/IMG_20130209_163630.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> An elevator next to Go Finch Bus Terminal.[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe main entrance to the North American Life Centre is not wheelchair-accessible, so you have to go around the building to use the side entrances (there are two of them) that are accessible.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"500\"]<a href=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\"><img class=\" \" alt=\"xerox building\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-eSTAQQwsFnE/URnQPBpK3EI/AAAAAAAAAN0/N3uG5QKWlw8/s1257/IMG_20130209_165320.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></a> Do not enter through this entrance because it is not wheelchair-accessible.[/caption]\r\n\r\nI took the video clips of myself walking from each of these entrances to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D1Gn55p4xsY\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IJ1boAcLoXo\r\n\r\nThe followings are the two clips from the two side entrances of North American Life Centre.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N1034YzoUw\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VqKYQmyb0JI\r\n\r\nAs you can see in the clips there is a lift in the stair passage from the lower level of North American Life Centre to the lower concourse level of the station. The problem with this lift is that you cannot get it to your level if it is on the other side.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q20clUbej5I\r\n\r\nThe landing instruction of the lift seems outdated or does not clearly explain how I could get the lift to my level. The only button I did not press is \"Call for assistance\", which I would find it annoying if I had to call the service attendant every time I use the lift.\r\n\r\nOnce you are inside the paid area, you can see the elevator next to the fare gate that leads to the subway platform, and you can also find the washroom, which is wheelchair-accessible. There are one wheelchair stall and two non-wheelchair stalls. The wheelchair stall is neither particularly cleaner nor dirtier than the other stalls.\r\n\r\nThere is also another elevator that leads to the upper level, where you take another elevator to the bus platform. I took another movie clip from the bus platform to the subway platform.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OY8ASFCOlw\r\n\r\nI am not a wheelchair user and there would be more stuff that I missed which the actual wheelchair users would find inconvenient, but I think there are two issues that need to be improved:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 13px;\">The lift needs to be fixed unless it is intentional to call for assistance every time the lift is used.</span></li>\r\n	<li>The North American Life Centre does not have a clear sign how to enter the building with wheelchairs. Either the building should make its main entrance wheelchair-accessible, or it should provide an explicit sign for its alternative accessible entrances.</li>\r\n</ol>','Accessible Routes to Finch TTC Station Subway Platform','','inherit','closed','open','','128-revision-32','','','2013-02-13 21:41:30','2013-02-14 02:41:30','',128,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/128-revision-32/',0,'revision','',0),(165,1,'2013-02-22 00:20:34','2013-02-22 05:20:34','I originally found the <a href=\"http://www.stopgapblog.blogspot.ca/\">StopGap</a> project from <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/life/2013/01/03/toronto_businesses_get_free_ramps_and_new_customers_in_wheelchairs.html\">an article in Toronto Star</a>, and I found this project truly inspiring.\r\n\r\nStopGap is a non-profit organization to remove the physical barriers so that every person can access every space without worries. And their first project is the community ramp project: build bright colourful ramps with donated materials and install them at the stores that are willing to have the ramps in their doorsteps.\r\n\r\nWhat I really like about this project is the attention that this little ramp can get; the ramp itself is probably not the best wheelchair ramp design ever, but its vivid colour with StopGap website address on it attracts people\'s attentions walking by. Also I could see that these ramps also give positive images to the local stores that have them. I think this project could raise awareness of accessibility issues, which is what we need to make our neighbourhood more accessible.\r\n\r\nHere are some pictures that we took while we were at Stouffville. StopGap is expanding to install the ramps on other towns, and you can see the full list of locations <a href=\"http://www.stopgapblog.blogspot.ca/p/ramp-locations.html\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_166\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/b07ef10a5cfd11e2a52022000a1f9e5e_7.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-166\" alt=\"yellow ramp\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/b07ef10a5cfd11e2a52022000a1f9e5e_7-300x300.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> yellow ramp.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-bFFC2OkssPk/UR8ByBZgzjI/AAAAAAAAAOk/2FDp-lAcrnI/s525/6da8099c5cfe11e2b68522000a1fb1ee_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"ramps\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-bFFC2OkssPk/UR8ByBZgzjI/AAAAAAAAAOk/2FDp-lAcrnI/s525/6da8099c5cfe11e2b68522000a1fb1ee_7.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> ramps[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-c3E5Cj87YnI/UR8ByK_OV0I/AAAAAAAAAOo/XD_glhxsW9A/s525/7d250a5a5cfe11e2aacd22000a1f932c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"red ramp\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-c3E5Cj87YnI/UR8ByK_OV0I/AAAAAAAAAOo/XD_glhxsW9A/s525/7d250a5a5cfe11e2aacd22000a1f932c_7.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> red ramp[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-Kru9fTTzyQI/UR8BzG7qgyI/AAAAAAAAAO0/Ht7dSJQG2yo/s525/d6c0db205cfe11e292a022000a1faf61_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"stouffville go station\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-Kru9fTTzyQI/UR8BzG7qgyI/AAAAAAAAAO0/Ht7dSJQG2yo/s525/d6c0db205cfe11e292a022000a1faf61_7.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> stouffville go station[/caption]','The Community Ramp Project - StopGap','','publish','closed','open','','the-community-ramp-project-stopgap','','','2013-02-23 17:28:54','2013-02-23 22:28:54','',0,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/?p=165',0,'post','',0),(166,1,'2013-02-15 22:58:53','2013-02-16 03:58:53','','b07ef10a5cfd11e2a52022000a1f9e5e_7','yellow ramp.','inherit','closed','open','','b07ef10a5cfd11e2a52022000a1f9e5e_7','','','2013-02-15 22:58:53','2013-02-16 03:58:53','',165,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/b07ef10a5cfd11e2a52022000a1f9e5e_7.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(167,1,'2013-02-15 22:58:16','2013-02-16 03:58:16','I originally found the StopGap project from <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/life/2013/01/03/toronto_businesses_get_free_ramps_and_new_customers_in_wheelchairs.html\">an article in Toronto Star</a>, and I found this project truly inspiring.\n\nStopGap is a non-profit organization to remove the physical barriers so that every person can access every space without worries. And their first project is the community ramp project: build bright colourful ramps with donated materials and install them at the stores that are willing to have the ramps in their doorsteps.\n\nWhat I really like about this project is the attention that this little ramp can get; the ramp itself is probably not the best wheelchair ramp design ever, but its vivid colour with StopGap website address on it attracts people\'s attentions nearby. Also I could see that these ramps also give positive images to the local stores that have them. I think this project could raise curiosity and awareness of accessibility issues, which is what we need to make our neighbourhood more accessible.\n\nHere are some pictures that we took while we were at Stouffville. StopGap is expanding to install the ramps on other towns, and you can see the full list of locations <a href=\"http://www.stopgapblog.blogspot.ca/p/ramp-locations.html\">here</a>.','The Community Ramp Project - StopGap','','inherit','closed','open','','165-revision','','','2013-02-15 22:58:16','2013-02-16 03:58:16','',165,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/165-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(168,1,'2013-02-15 23:02:45','2013-02-16 04:02:45','I originally found the StopGap project from <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/life/2013/01/03/toronto_businesses_get_free_ramps_and_new_customers_in_wheelchairs.html\">an article in Toronto Star</a>, and I found this project truly inspiring.\r\n\r\nStopGap is a non-profit organization to remove the physical barriers so that every person can access every space without worries. And their first project is the community ramp project: build bright colourful ramps with donated materials and install them at the stores that are willing to have the ramps in their doorsteps.\r\n\r\nWhat I really like about this project is the attention that this little ramp can get; the ramp itself is probably not the bes