on]','The Community Ramp Project - StopGap','','inherit','closed','open','','165-revision-12','','','2013-02-22 00:20:09','2013-02-22 05:20:09','',165,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/165-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(187,1,'2013-02-22 00:20:34','2013-02-22 05:20:34','I originally found the StopGap project from <a href=\"http://www.thestar.com/life/2013/01/03/toronto_businesses_get_free_ramps_and_new_customers_in_wheelchairs.html\">an article in Toronto Star</a>, and I found this project truly inspiring.\r\n\r\nStopGap is a non-profit organization to remove the physical barriers so that every person can access every space without worries. And their first project is the community ramp project: build bright colourful ramps with donated materials and install them at the stores that are willing to have the ramps in their doorsteps.\r\n\r\nWhat I really like about this project is the attention that this little ramp can get; the ramp itself is probably not the best wheelchair ramp design ever, but its vivid colour with StopGap website address on it attracts people\'s attentions walking by. Also I could see that these ramps also give positive images to the local stores that have them. I think this project could raise awareness of accessibility issues, which is what we need to make our neighbourhood more accessible.\r\n\r\nHere are some pictures that we took while we were at Stouffville. StopGap is expanding to install the ramps on other towns, and you can see the full list of locations <a href=\"http://www.stopgapblog.blogspot.ca/p/ramp-locations.html\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_166\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/b07ef10a5cfd11e2a52022000a1f9e5e_7.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-166\" alt=\"yellow ramp\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/b07ef10a5cfd11e2a52022000a1f9e5e_7-300x300.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> yellow ramp.[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-bFFC2OkssPk/UR8ByBZgzjI/AAAAAAAAAOk/2FDp-lAcrnI/s525/6da8099c5cfe11e2b68522000a1fb1ee_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"ramps\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-bFFC2OkssPk/UR8ByBZgzjI/AAAAAAAAAOk/2FDp-lAcrnI/s525/6da8099c5cfe11e2b68522000a1fb1ee_7.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> ramps[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-c3E5Cj87YnI/UR8ByK_OV0I/AAAAAAAAAOo/XD_glhxsW9A/s525/7d250a5a5cfe11e2aacd22000a1f932c_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"red ramp\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-c3E5Cj87YnI/UR8ByK_OV0I/AAAAAAAAAOo/XD_glhxsW9A/s525/7d250a5a5cfe11e2aacd22000a1f932c_7.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> red ramp[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-Kru9fTTzyQI/UR8BzG7qgyI/AAAAAAAAAO0/Ht7dSJQG2yo/s525/d6c0db205cfe11e292a022000a1faf61_7.jpg\"><img alt=\"stouffville go station\" src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-Kru9fTTzyQI/UR8BzG7qgyI/AAAAAAAAAO0/Ht7dSJQG2yo/s525/d6c0db205cfe11e292a022000a1faf61_7.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a> stouffville go station[/caption]','The Community Ramp Project - StopGap','','inherit','closed','open','','165-revision-13','','','2013-02-22 00:20:34','2013-02-22 05:20:34','',165,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/165-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(189,1,'2013-03-01 00:09:18','2013-03-01 05:09:18','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-190\" alt=\"financial program\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere are several programs that provide financial supports to people with disabilities. For instance, Registered Disability Savings Plan (RDSP) can provide up to $90,000 for the entire lifetime. Canada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefits is a monthly payment (~$841.95/month, 2012-basis) to people who are eligible for the benefit. Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities provides students $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\r\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\r\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) in a way that the earnings from your savings will remain tax-free until you withdraw money out of the RDSP later. You need to have Social Insurance Number (SIN) to be considered eligible and the lifetime contribution limit is $200,000, although there is no annual limit.\r\n\r\nThe government provides two additional financial support programs that could match your RDSP savings up to maximum $90,000 over your lifetime: Canada Disability Savings Grant and Canada Disability Savings Bond.\r\n<h3>Canada Disability Savings Grant</h3>\r\nCanada Disability Savings Grant (CDSG) is a matching grant that the government deposits into your RDSP. The maximum grant amount is $3,500 / year and the lifetime amount is $70,000, but the actual amount depends on the family income and the amount of annual savings.\r\n\r\nIf the family income is below $87,123, then the government gives $3,500 for $1,500 contributed a year. You may contribute more than $1,500, but there is no more matching grant beyond $1,500. If the family income is above $87,123, then the government gives $1,000 for $1,000 contributed a year. You may contribute more than $1,000, but there is no more matching grant beyond $1,000. You can receive the government grant up to $70,000 for your lifetime.\r\n<h3>Canada Disability Savings Bond</h3>\r\nCanada Disability Savings Bond (CDSB) is a program for low-income and modest-income families whose annual income is below $43,561. The government will deposit $1,000 / year to your RDSP if your income is below $25,356, and this amount will decrease as your annual income increases. If your annual income is above $43,561, there is no more benefit. You do not need to make any contribution to your RDSP to receive the benefit. You can receive the bond amount up to $20,000 for your lifetime.\r\n<h2>Canada Pension Plan Disability Benefit</h2>\r\nCanada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefit is a monthly benefit available to individuals who has made enough contributions to the CPP, but could not work any longer because of disability. You may be considered eligible if you are under 65, stopped working because of a medical condition, and has contributed to the CPP while working.\r\n\r\nThe actual monthly amount depends on how much you have contributed to the CPP, but the average amount was $841.95 / month on 2012, and the maximum amount was $1212.90 / month. The amount will be re-adjusted on January every year if there are increases in the cost of living.\r\n<h2>Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities</h2>\r\nThere is a grant available to students studying in universities and post-secondary institutions. If you apply and qualify for a Canada Student Loan, you can be eligible for receiving this grant as well. You can receive $2,000 per academic year to help cover your tuition, books, and accommodation costs.','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','publish','closed','open','','financial-assistance-for-people-with-disabilities','','','2013-03-01 00:09:18','2013-03-01 05:09:18','',0,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/?p=189',0,'post','',0),(190,1,'2013-02-26 21:54:58','2013-02-27 02:54:58','','rdsp','','inherit','closed','open','','rdsp','','','2013-02-26 21:54:58','2013-02-27 02:54:58','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(191,1,'2013-02-26 22:05:41','2013-02-27 03:05:41','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium