tudents $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\r\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\r\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) in a way that the earnings from your savings will remain tax-free until you withdraw money out of the RDSP later. You need to have Social Insurance Number (SIN) to be considered eligible and the lifetime contribution limit is $200,000, although there is no annual limit.\r\n\r\nThe government provides two additional financial support programs that could match your RDSP savings up to maximum $90,000 over your lifetime: Canada Disability Savings Grant (CDSG) and Canada Disability Savings Bond (CDSB).','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','inherit','closed','open','','189-revision-2','','','2013-02-26 22:06:41','2013-02-27 03:06:41','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/189-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(193,1,'2013-02-26 22:06:46','2013-02-27 03:06:46','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-190\" alt=\"financial program\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere are several programs that can provide financial supports to people with disabilities. For instance, Registered Disability Savings Plan (RDSP) can provide up to $90,000 over your lifetime. Canada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefits is a monthly payment (~$841.95/month, 2012-basis) to people who are eligible for the benefit. Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities provides students $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\r\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\r\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) in a way that the earnings from your savings will remain tax-free until you withdraw money out of the RDSP later. You need to have Social Insurance Number (SIN) to be considered eligible and the lifetime contribution limit is $200,000, although there is no annual limit.\r\n\r\nThe government provides two additional financial support programs that could match your RDSP savings up to maximum $90,000 over your lifetime: Canada Disability Savings Grant (CDSG) and Canada Disability Savings Bond (CDSB).','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','inherit','closed','open','','189-revision-3','','','2013-02-26 22:06:46','2013-02-27 03:06:46','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/189-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(194,1,'2013-02-26 22:07:57','2013-02-27 03:07:57','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-190\" alt=\"financial program\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere are several programs that can provide financial supports to people with disabilities. For instance, Registered Disability Savings Plan (RDSP) can provide up to $90,000 over your lifetime. Canada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefits is a monthly payment (~$841.95/month, 2012-basis) to people who are eligible for the benefit. Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities provides students $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\r\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\r\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) in a way that the earnings from your savings will remain tax-free until you withdraw money out of the RDSP later. You need to have Social Insurance Number (SIN) to be considered eligible and the lifetime contribution limit is $200,000, although there is no annual limit.\r\n\r\nThe government provides two additional financial support programs that could match your RDSP savings up to maximum $90,000 over your lifetime: Canada Disability Savings Grant and Canada Disability Savings Bond.\r\n\r\n<h3>Canada Disability Savings Grant</h3>\r\n\r\nCanada Disability Savings Grant (CDSG) is a matching grant that the government deposits into your RDSP.','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','inherit','closed','open','','189-revision-4','','','2013-02-26 22:07:57','2013-02-27 03:07:57','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/189-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(195,1,'2013-02-26 22:08:01','2013-02-27 03:08:01','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-190\" alt=\"financial program\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere are several programs that can provide financial supports to people with disabilities. For instance, Registered Disability Savings Plan (RDSP) can provide up to $90,000 over your lifetime. Canada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefits is a monthly payment (~$841.95/month, 2012-basis) to people who are eligible for the benefit. Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities provides students $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\r\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\r\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) in a way that the earnings from your savings will remain tax-free until you withdraw money out of the RDSP later. You need to have Social Insurance Number (SIN) to be considered eligible and the lifetime contribution limit is $200,000, although there is no annual limit.\r\n\r\nThe government provides two additional financial support programs that could match your RDSP savings up to maximum $90,000 over your lifetime: Canada Disability Savings Grant and Canada Disability Savings Bond.\r\n<h3>Canada Disability Savings Grant</h3>\r\nCanada Disability Savings Grant (CDSG) is a matching grant that the government deposits into your RDSP.','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','inherit','closed','open','','189-revision-5','','','2013-02-26 22:08:01','2013-02-27 03:08:01','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/189-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(196,1,'2013-02-26 22:59:42','2013-02-27 03:59:42','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-190\" alt=\"financial program\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\n\nThere are several programs that can provide financial supports to people with disabilities. For instance, Registered Disability Savings Plan (RDSP) can provide up to $90,000 over your lifetime. Canada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefits is a monthly payment (~$841.95/month, 2012-basis) to people who are eligible for the benefit. Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities provides students $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) in a way that the earnings from your savings will remain tax-free until you withdraw money out of the RDSP later. You need to have Social Insurance Number (SIN) to be considered eligible and the lifetime contribution limit is $200,000, although there is no annual limit.\n\nThe government provides two additional financial support programs that could match your RDSP savings up to maximum $90,000 over your lifetime: Canada Disability Savings Grant and Canada Disability Savings Bond.\n<h3>Canada Disability Savings Grant</h3>\nCanada Disability Savings Grant (CDSG) is a matching grant that the government deposits into your RDSP. The maximum grant amount is $3,500 / year and the lifetime amount is $70,000, but the actual amount depends on the family income and the amount of annual savings.\n\nIf the family income is below $87,123, then the government gives $3,500 for $1,500 contributed a year. You may contribute more than $1,500, but there is no more matching grant beyond $1,500. If the family income is above $87,123, then the government gives $1,000 for $1,000 contributed a year. You may contribute more than $1,000, but there is no more matching grant beyond $1,000. You can receive the government grant up to $70,000 for your lifetime.\n<h3>Canada Disability Savings Bond</h3>\nCanada Disability Savings Bond (CDSB) is a program for low-income and modest-income families whose annual income is below $43,561. The government will deposit $1,000 / year to your RDSP if your income is below $25,356, and this amount will decrease as your annual income increases. If your annual income is above $43,561, there is no more benefit. You do not need to make any contribution to your RDSP to receive the benefit. You can receive the bond amount up to $20,000 for your lifetime.\n<h2>Canada Pension Plan Disability Benefit</h2>\nCanada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefit is a monthly benefit available to individuals who has made enough contributions to the CPP, but could not work any longer because of disability. You may be considered eligible if you are under 65, stopped working because of a medical condition, and has contributed to the CPP while working.\n\nThe actual monthly amount depends on how much you have contributed to the CPP, but the average amount was $841.95 / month on 2012, and the maximum amount was $1212.90 / month. The amount will be re-adjusted on January every year if there are increases in the cost of living.\n\n<h2>Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities<\n\nThere is a grant available to students studying in universities and post-secondary institutions.','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','inherit','closed','open','','189-revision-6','','','2013-02-26 22:59:42','2013-02-27 03:59:42','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/189-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(197,1,'2013-02-26 23:00:35','2013-02-27 04:00:35','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-190\" alt=\"financial program\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThere are several programs that can provide financial supports to people with disabilities. For instance, Registered Disability Savings Plan (RDSP) can provide up to $90,000 over your lifetime. Canada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefits is a monthly payment (~$841.95/month, 2012-basis) to people who are eligible for the benefit. Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities provides students $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\r\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\r\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) in a way that the earnings from your savings will remain tax-free until you withdraw money out of the RDSP later. You need to have Social Insurance Number (SIN) to be considered eligible and the lifetime contribution limit is $200,000, although there is no annual limit.\r\n\r\nThe government provides two additional financial support programs that could match your RDSP savings up to maximum $90,000 over your lifetime: Canada Disability Savings Grant and Canada Disability Savings Bond.\r\n<h3>Canada Disability Savings Grant</h3>\r\nCanada Disability Savings Grant (CDSG) is a matching grant that the governm