considered eligible if you are under 65, stopped working because of a medical condition, and has contributed to the CPP while working.\r\n\r\nThe actual monthly amount depends on how much you have contributed to the CPP, but the average amount was $841.95 / month on 2012, and the maximum amount was $1212.90 / month. The amount will be re-adjusted on January every year if there are increases in the cost of living.\r\n<h2>Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities</h2>\r\nThere is a grant available to students studying in universities and post-secondary institutions. If you apply and qualify for a Canada Student Loan, you can be eligible for receiving this grant as well. You can receive $2,000 per academic year to help cover your tuition, books, and accommodation costs.','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','inherit','closed','open','','189-revision-14','','','2013-03-01 00:04:51','2013-03-01 05:04:51','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/189-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(205,1,'2013-03-01 00:10:20','2013-03-01 05:10:20','<a href=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-190\" alt=\"financial program\" src=\"http://savewheelchairtrans.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/rdsp-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\n\nThere are several programs that provide financial supports to people with disabilities. For instance, Registered Disability Savings Plan (RDSP) can provide up to $90,000 for the entire lifetime. Canada Pension Plan (CPP) Disability Benefits is a monthly payment (~$841.95/month, 2012-basis) to people who are eligible for the benefit. Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities provides students $2,000 / year to help cover their tuition expenses.\n<h2>Registered Disability Savings Plan</h2>\nThis is a long-term savings plan available for individuals who are under 60 and eligible for the Disability Tax Credit. It is similar to a Registered Retirement 