not work any longer because of disability. You may be considered eligible if you are under 65, stopped working because of a medical condition, and has contributed to the CPP while working.\n\nThe actual monthly amount depends on how much you have contributed to the CPP, but the average amount was $841.95 / month on 2012, and the maximum amount was $1212.90 / month. The amount will be re-adjusted on January every year if there are increases in the cost of living.\n<h2>Grant for Students with Permanent Disabilities</h2>\nThere is a grant available to students studying in universities and post-secondary institutions. If you apply and qualify for a Canada Student Loan, you can be eligible for receiving this grant as well. You can receive $2,000 per academic year to help cover your tuition, books, and accommodation costs.','Financial Assistance for People with Disabilities','','inherit','closed','open','','189-autosave','','','2013-03-01 00:10:20','2013-03-01 05:10:20','',189,'http://savewheelchairtrans.com/189-autosave/',0,'revision','',0);
